**CRITICAL TERMINOLOGY RULES:**
- Use "microscopic" for <0.1mm (NOT "tiny", "very small", "barely visible")
- Use "minor" for 0.1-0.3mm (NOT "slight", "small", "light")
- Use "moderate" for 0.3-1mm (NOT "medium", "noticeable", "clear")
- Use "heavy" for >1mm (NOT "severe", "major", "significant")

This ensures consistency in all grading documentation and analysis.

---

DEFECT-SPECIFIC DEFINITIONS
----------------------------

Whitening (mm)           Visible white region or missing ink at a corner or edge; measure linear length.
                         Detection: Color deviation from expected ink/border color using Î”E > 6 threshold.
                         Exposed card stock (white/light tan) underneath darker print layer.
                         Severity Scale:
                         - Microscopic (<0.1mm): Barely visible even under close inspection
                         - Minor (0.1-0.3mm): Visible upon close inspection
                         - Moderate (0.3-1mm): Easily visible to naked eye
                         - Heavy (>1mm): Obvious whitening, significant exposed stock

Roughness / Chip         Edge deviation or nick exposing lighter base stock color.
                         Detection: Compare local pixel color against adjacent printed areas.
                         Edge deviation > 0.05mm AND color change Î”E > 6 = chipping detected.
                         Severity Scale:
                         - Microscopic (<0.1mm): Individual micro-chips
                         - Minor (0.1-0.3mm): Small chips or 1-2 white dots
                         - Moderate (0.3-1mm): Visible chipping or multiple dots
                         - Heavy (>1mm): Extensive material loss

Abrasion / Rubbing       Dull patches or inconsistent reflectivity along edges or surface.
                         Detection: Loss of glossy finish, surface texture change, lightened color.
                         Often appears as matte finish compared to surrounding glossy areas.
                         Severity Scale:
                         - Microscopic (<2mm): Barely perceptible dull spot
                         - Minor (2-5mm): Localized loss of gloss
                         - Moderate (5-10mm): Obvious abrasion patch
                         - Heavy (>10mm): Extensive surface wear

Crease Severity          Fold line in card surface:
                         - Light Crease: Single visible line that does not break surface gloss (Max grade: 4.5)
                         - Moderate Crease: Line that interrupts surface reflection but not paper layer (Max grade: 3.0)
                         - Heavy Crease: Fold that distorts paper or image plane (Max grade: 2.0)

Print Dot                Single contrasting pixel â‰¥ 0.1 mm diameter not in design.
                         Common on solid backgrounds. May be factory defect (acceptable if slight).
                         Severity: Based on size and quantity using Universal Scale above.

Hairline Scratch         Scratch < 0.2 mm wide / < 5 mm long visible only under reflected light.
                         Severity: Minor (by definition, falls in 0.1-0.3mm range)

Visible Scratch          Scratch â‰¥ 0.2 mm wide or â‰¥ 5 mm long visible in normal lighting.
                         Severity: Moderate or Heavy depending on size and location.

Centering Ratio          (Narrower border Ã· Wider border) Ã— 100 = % balance; e.g. 45/55 = centered within 10%.

Rounding                 Corner curve radius indicating loss of sharp 90Â° angle:
                         - Minor rounding: 0.2-0.5mm radius
                         - Moderate rounding: 0.5-1mm radius
                         - Heavy rounding: >1mm radius

